In-domain approaches are trained with a Conv5 architecture, while PsCo cross-domain is trained on a ResNet-50 architecture. Table 1 provides an overview of the experimental results for both the 5-way 1-shot and the 5-way 5-shot scenarios.
The results demonstrate that CAMeLU outperforms the existing UML methods, regardless of the difference in the evaluation setting. As highlighted in Section 4.1, CACTUs, UMTRA, and Meta-GMVAE are evaluated only in-domain, requiring knowledge about the test domain prior to training. This is not necessary for CAMeLU as it demonstrates high performance in the challenging cross-domain scenario.
Even compared to PsCo, the only UML method designed for cross-domain applications, CAMeLU exhibits a performance improvement in all datasets except miniImageNet, where PsCo achieves even better results than the supervised CAML. This is expected, as the model utilized for cross-domain evaluation of PsCo is pre-trained on ImageNet-1k, which includes the images of miniImageNet, leading to data leakage. Furthermore, PsCo requires a fine-tuning phase to adapt to the test domain, whereas CAMeLU achieves good performance with a single forward pass, enhancing its applicability to real-time applications.
It is also worth noting that CAMeLU achieves comparable performance to its supervised counterpart, CAML, when evaluated on miniImageNet and CIFAR-fs and it even outperforms CAML when evaluated on more dissimilar domains, such as CUB and Aircraft. This highlights the efficacy of the task construction strategy used in CAMeLU, which acts as a sort of task augmentation and enhances the generalization capability of the model.

We compare our results with UML methods, a supervised meta-learning method, and two SSL methods. For the UML baselines, we consider CACTUs-MAML [18], CACTUs-ProtoNet [18], UMTRA [20], Meta-GMVAE [25], and PsCo [19]. All these methods are evaluated in-domain, i.e., using the same dataset for training and evaluation, to adhere to the setting proposed in the original papers. Only PsCo is also extended to the cross-domain scenario that we discuss in this paper.
All methods are trained for 100100100 epochs, using the parameters reported in the original papers [20, 18, 25, 19], and evaluated with 100100100 adaptation steps on each task when required by the model.
When evaluated in-domain, all approaches use a Conv5 architecture consisting of 555 convolutional layers with 646464 filters and a kernel size of 333, followed by batch normalization, ReLU non-linearity, max pooling, and a classifier head. The only exception is Meta-GMVAE. For this method, the authors trained a Conv5 feature extractor with SimCLR and input the learned features into a variational autoencoder (VAE) [25]. Due to time limitations and the computational resources required to train a model with SimCLR, in our experiments, we used a feature extractor consisting of a pre-trained version of SimCLR on ResNet-50 [3], followed by a projection layer fine-tuned for 100100100 steps to the training dataset, as done for the SSL baselines. This approach results in a better performance than the one reported in the original paper (see Table 1), likely due to the improved ability of the feature extractor to extract meaningful features. For PsCo, when evaluated on a cross-domain setting, we utilized the ResNet-50 architecture trained on ImageNet-1k, and we then applied the model to the test domain using 100100100 adaptation steps to it.

Additionally, a comparison of CAMeLU‚Äôs performance when trained on miniImageNet (Table 8), on ImageNet-964 (Table 1), and on a large-scale dataset (Table 2) show that our method is only slightly affected by the size of the training dataset. This robustness enhances CAMeLU‚Äôs applicability to scenarios where only a small unlabeled training dataset is available, which is common in real-world applications.

We conduct additional experiments to evaluate how CAMeLU performs when trained on a large-scale dataset. As our focus is cross-domain classification through in-context learning, we hypothesize that training on a dataset spanning various concepts enhances classification performance, as suggested in [12, 31].
To this effect, we combine three training datasets with different levels of granularity: ImageNet-964 [8], MSCOCO [27], and Fungi [38]. At each training episode, a dataset is uniformly sampled, and NùëÅN data points are subsequently extracted. These samples are then utilized in our method as described in Section 3.
Table 2 presents the results for CAMeLU and the supervised CAML method. Notably, training on a combination of multiple datasets (denoted as mds in Table 2) yields improved performance compared to training solely on ImageNet-964. However, the performance gap is not substantial, likely due to the large size of ImageNet-964 (around 80%percent8080\% of the overall dataset), resulting in its more frequent selection compared to the other datasets. Therefore, to optimize computational resources and time, we conducted all the remaining experiments by training only on ImageNet-964.

Additionally, a comparison of CAMeLU‚Äôs performance when trained on miniImageNet (Table 8), on ImageNet-964 (Table 1), and on a large-scale dataset (Table 2) show that our method is only slightly affected by the size of the training dataset. This robustness enhances CAMeLU‚Äôs applicability to scenarios where only a small unlabeled training dataset is available, which is common in real-world applications.

The symbol ‚Ä†‚Ä†\dagger indicates results that are affected by data leakage. Results show the mean and standard deviations across three complete runs of the algorithms.

In this section, we compare CAMeLU with SimCLR [7] and SwAV [6]. For training SSL methods in our experiments, we employed a backbone network with a ResNet-50 architecture pre-trained on ImageNet-1k and obtained from PyTorch Lightning Bolts [3]. To facilitate model adaptation to the test domain, we fine-tuned a classification layer on top of the pre-trained backbone using SGD with initial learning rate of 0.010.010.01, momentum of 0.90.90.9, weight decay of 10‚àí4superscript10410^{-4}, and 100100100 fine-tuning steps per task, following [19]. This setup differs from the evaluation setting used in CAMeLU, where predictions are obtained with a single forward pass, leveraging the in-context learning ability of transformer architectures. However, SSL approaches must adapt to the test domain before label predictions, resulting in a less challenging evaluation setting than CAMeLU.
Results for SSL approaches are averaged over 500500500 test tasks and presented in Table 3.
While SSL approaches outperform CAMeLU on miniImageNet and CIFAR-fs, their performance decreases when evaluated on the other datasets. CUB and Aircraft are two fine-grained datasets significantly different from ImageNet-1k, challenging the transferability of features learned by SSL methods to these datasets. Moreover, the high performance on miniImageNet may be attributed to data leakage with ImageNet-1k, as discussed in Section 4.2. CAMeLU, in contrast, demonstrates effective generalization to tasks sampled from these datasets, once again highlighting its generalization ability over mere memorization.

The symbol ‚Ä†‚Ä†\dagger indicates results that are affected by data leakage. Results show the mean and standard deviations across three complete runs of the algorithms.

To assess the impact of the pre-trained feature extractor, we evaluate CAMeLU with various extractors trained using different strategies. In particular, we compare the effectiveness of a ResNet-50 encoder pre-trained in a supervised manner, a ResNet-50 pre-trained using two SSL strategies, i.e., SimCLR [7] and SwAV [6], and a ViT-B/16 architecture trained with CLIP [34]. The encoders are downloaded from the Hugging Face [54] and PyTorch Lightning Bolts [3] websites and pre-trained on ImageNet-1k [8], except for the CLIP model, which is pre-trained on a large dataset with 400400400 million (image, text) pairs [34].
Results in Table 7(a) demonstrate that the models pre-trained on ImageNet-1k exhibit significantly higher performance on miniImageNet, compared to other datasets, primarily due to the data leakage issue described in Section 4.2.
Interestingly, the supervised ResNet-50 outperforms other feature extractors on three out of four datasets. However, on the Aircraft dataset, CAMeLU, trained with CLIP - ViT-B/16, emerges as the best-performing method. Furthermore, when training CAMeLU with a multi-dataset approach (Table 7(b)), as described in Section 4.5, results for CLIP-ViT-B/16 improve significantly, bridging the performance gap with the supervised encoder across all datasets except miniImageNet.
Indeed, CLIP is dataset-agnostic and capable of learning a representation for a wide set of tasks, enhancing its applicability to datasets significantly different from those used for training [34]. Therefore, as the scope of this work is leveraging in-context learning properties for cross-domain inference with no fine-tuning, we decided to use the CLIP-ViT-B/16 feature extractor in our model.
Additionally, our experiments suggest that CAMeLU‚Äôs performance scales with the strength of the feature extractor, indicating potential for further investigation as more robust feature extractors become available.

S7.T8.caption: Table 8: Accuracy results obtained training PsCo and CAMeLU with a small-scale dataset, namely miniImageNet. This is denoted as (mini) in the table. Results show both in-domain performance (on the test set of miniImageNet) and cross-domain performance on CIFAR-fs, CUB, and Aircraft. The mean and standard deviation across three complete runs of the algorithms are reported.
references:
While most studies on training transformer architectures focus on large-scale training datasets, we investigate the generalization capabilities of our proposed approach using a small-scale training dataset. Specifically, we train CAMeLU on miniImageNet and evaluate its performance both in-domain (i.e., on the test set of miniImageNet) and cross-domain on CIFAR-fs, CUB, and Aircraft.
CAMeLU demonstrates effective generalization in this scenario, showing impressive performance in both in-domain and cross-domain settings, as shown in Table 8, surpassing PsCo by a large margin.

Additionally, a comparison of CAMeLU‚Äôs performance when trained on miniImageNet (Table 8), on ImageNet-964 (Table 1), and on a large-scale dataset (Table 2) show that our method is only slightly affected by the size of the training dataset. This robustness enhances CAMeLU‚Äôs applicability to scenarios where only a small unlabeled training dataset is available, which is common in real-world applications.
